 involved in the demonstration and measurement of natural selection, presents the critical evidence for its existence, and places it in an evolutionary perspective. Professor Endler finds that there are a remarkable number of direct demonstrations of selection in a wide variety of animals and plants. The distribution of observed magnitudes of selection in natural populations is surprisingly broad, and it overlaps extensively the range of values found in artificial selection. He argues that the common assumption that selection is usually weak in natural populations is no longer tenable, but that natural selection is only one component of the process of evolution; natural selection can explain the change of frequencies of variants, but not their origins.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNatural selection. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aJohnson, Samuel, "ations.  aabsolute fitness.  aartificial selection.  abehavior.  acause and causal relationships.  aclines.  acolor patterns.  acovariance effects.  adensity-dependent selection.  adevelopmental effects.  aecology, effects of.  aequilibrium.  aerosion analogy.  afossil data.  afrequency-dependent selection.  afunction and design.  alaboratory populations.  alifetime fitness.  amorphological traits.  amutants and mutation.  aorigin of alkies and variants.  arare events.  astabilizing selection.  atautology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209517.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_E